When he's not building robots that talk, or relaxing around the house with his brothers, you can find this quiet but friendly M.Eng student rollerblading along the Charles River, playing old-school video games, or singing in our chapter's very own in-house a capella group. His ever-present smile and unusual, sharply sarcastic sense of humor have been known to brighten the sometimes long and oppressive days that MIT students face.
A native of the sunflower state, Charlie was a serious musician in high school, although his recent schedule has left him little time for the clarinet or piano. His favorite vacation is a trip to the Rocky Mountains, where life is simple and relaxed, and his love-hate relationship with MIT can be momentarily forgotten.
The son of two teachers, Charlie enjoying learning and teaching in all of their various forms. Among his many passions are classical music, computer science, and foreign languages. But by far his deepest passion at MIT is for the fraternity that has helped him grow immensely as a person, has served as a family away from home, and has made his years at MIT more memorable than he ever thought possible.
For new MIT students, Charlie offers this bit of advice: Life only gives you one chance to be part of a collegiate brotherhood. College is a special time in your life, a time that you'll want to make the most of. So even if, like many of us here at Sigma Nu, you were always sure that fraternities aren't for you, you owe it to yourself to check them out. Who knows, it might turn out to be the best decision you make at MIT. It certainly was for us.

John Velasco is a rising senior focusing on National Security Studies in the Department of Political Science at MIT.
At MIT, John’s served as the Student Government Treasurer and is currently the Senior Class Vice President. In the local community, John has started a math mentoring program for 8th graders that is currently at 5 schools in the district surrounding MIT.
During the past two summers, John has had the unique opportunity to pursue his interest in working for the Federal Government. During last summer, John worked as an analyst for the Money Laundering Division of the United States Postal Inspection Service, Boston Division. In this capacity, John had the opportunity to conduct hands-on criminal investigations, do field work, meet with other agents from the FBI, Secret Service, and ICE (Immigrations & Customs Enforcement), as well as do formal presentations for Assistant United States’ Attorneys. His fondest memory of the summer was the day when he got to participate in firearms training right alongside other Federal agents.
This summer, John worked in Washington, D.C. for the Chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, Congressman Duncan Hunter. In this capacity John has had the opportunity to attend committee hearings and meet officials such as Attorney General John Ashcroft and FBI Director Robert Mueller. He has also got to work on a number of research projects, such as the researching the threat posed by manPADS (shoulder launched missiles) to commercial jets, which has had a direct affect on legislation in the House of Representatives.
After MIT, John plans to pursue a Ph.D. focusing in the area of foreign counterintelligence. He hopes to work for the new domestic intelligence agency of the FBI or in the Central Intelligence Agency.

I won't be sleeping much this August, have to introduce incoming freshmen to the wonderful world of Ocean Engineering! (I'm the Super-Mentor for Discover Ocean Engineering.)
I am currently involved in a myriad of activites outside of class here at MIT. I am a member of the MIT ROV Team, we build underwater robots for an annual competition (this year at NASA's Neutral Buoyancy Lab). I am the President of the MIT SCUBA Club, you should join if you're a certified diver here at MIT, especially if you normally rent gear (we have discounted rates at local dive shops for members). I'm also a VP for 13SEAS, the Ocean Engineering student-professional group.
I have UROPed since my freshman IAP, and would recommend it to all MIT students. I went to two conferences in fall 2004 to present my research, one in Houston, Texas and the other in Kobe, Japan.
Recently, I started working on another project studying the hydrodynamic effects of leading-edge tubercles on humpback whale fins. This might lead to better wings, rudders, propellers, what have you... I'll be extending this project into a Master's Thesis for my fifth year at MIT.
Summer 2004 I was busy redesigning a life support system for deep ocean exploration and bioprospecting (cure for cancer, AIDS, whatever ails you).
Summer 2005 I worked for Shell Exploration & Production. I'm working on inspection & maintenance scheduling, subsidence issues, and platform modification feasibility.
You can do anything you want here if you work hard enough, but be careful not to spread too thin.

I am such a crusty alumnus.
I cook for myself, go to bed early, wake up around 10 on the weekends when I sleep in, and most importantly, I work 9-5 five days a week.
Don't get me wrong, it's amazing! I have my weekends free to do whatever I like (no homework) so all of you students can quit your sniggering! Besides, I'm headed off to med school this July, so this bout of free time will shortly be only a memory.
Living cheaply and watching money pile up is also fun, but not as much fun as spending said pile. I highly recommend building your own computer superspec'd for gaming, if you're into that. That said, don't get addicted. It took me three months to "get over" WoW, and I still have pangs of regret over quitting. ;(
Make the most of MIT, you'll miss it. Be thankful you have things like Facebook, though, because keeping friends is the most important thing in the world and you'll want to use everything at your disposal to keep in touch.
Best of luck in classes to all you young'uns and don't forget to have fun!

Welcome, and thanks for checking out my house! I have the incredible privilege of living in a community with thirty other guys. We have a beautiful hundred-year-old brownstone in Boston, with huge rooms and good food, but the reason I love this place is most definitely the people - guys who really care about each other, the college experience, and this place.
I never expected to join a fraternity before leaving high school, but among the MIT fraternity men I met people more like myself that I ever imagined - motivated, enthusiastic, excited about life, and full of lofty ideals. I did rush activities simply because they were tons of fun, and at the end of rush Sigma Nu extended me a bid. After a hard decision process, I decided to accept. It was the right decision. The longer I live here, the more excited I am about Sigma Nu. The opportunity for community is completely unique, and it’s an awesome place to learn from each other.
This semester I will serve my second term as House Chaplain, an elected office focused on developing brotherhood, increasing internal morale, and ministering to the spiritual needs of my brothers. The door is open. I can see the inside of the room, there is a wooden table and three chairs. The light is dim, and the dust forms an indissoluble mist that floats over the few scattered objects inside. I feel it, the smell of old flooding the environment. As I cross the portal, it blows into my face, dense and clear, it smells like death inside. The portraits are broken and their shattered glasses fill the ground. The pictures are getting old, not only because of their black and white printing, but because humidity has erased their faces. The old piano lies silent, covered in dust, black and long, waiting to be played, to disturb the silence, and the waves of dust with the sounds of its broken strings. I don't open the lid, a collage of broken keys scattered in the floor makes me imagine the void below it.
Tell me what is happening, she says, while I look at her in silence, tell me please, tell me, she repeats, I look at her watery eyes without answering, tell me. My mouth is shut, mute. As she is, I am also dying to know what is happening. I feel that it, here, inside, in my chest, flowing, flooding my soul with the whispers of silence, with the coldest of all fires, the flame of nostalgia.
Fire in the sky, the flames burn in the middle of the first starry night in a week. She is there, watching as I see the reflections of the flames in her eyes. I don't feel it, the joy of others, I don't scream it, the day is not mine, I am lost in a strange land. I ask her about the green that sometimes transports me thousands of kilometers to the south. Maybe we are conquering you, I joke, maybe, she replies. Even with the catalysis of alcohol, they are different, while the slightest touch explodes in my skin as the fireworks in the sky, they need to crash into each other to feel.
The music fades into an amorphous sound of beats and movement that fills me, that explodes inside me. We move, spin, dance, shout as the world seems to reduce to our bodies, our faces, our lips. Her lips taste like ocean, they are as blue as her eyes, clean, and empty, sometimes salty and herbaceous. Our kiss is a contradiction, while it is the shout of my silence, it is the silence among her shouts. While is an implosive crash for her, it is an explosion for me. I am incomplete, lost in a land that is not of my own, lost in a collage of strange colors, of different sounds, here, I can't hear the melody of the indigenous flute, there are no trees of perennial foliage to inspire it, there is no tropical summer to feed it. It is both the first and the last kiss, a fugacious moment for both, that fades after one night, that dies after one day. It is not love, nor desire what inspires it, but thirst, an insatiable thirst, an unbeatable hunger that erodes my soul.
Water, below and above, water, it surrounds me, water. It flows, cold, moving faster than my body, water. The river is clean, its soil is muddy and grassy, some pebbles lie scattered here and there, forming intricate designs changed every day by the relentless current. The trees satiate their thirst by throwing the snakes of their roots into the water. The air is filled with the sounds of the wilderness, screams of parrots and magpies, followed by their erratic fly under a purple sky. Some fish approach, I can feel the contact of their tiny mouths in my skin, I try to scare them, but I can't move, I'm imprisoned inside myself. The soar in my leg has faded, the rattlesnake poison has diluted into my bloodstream. I felt it in my brain, crawling, and piercing into my consciousness. Now I don't feel any pain in my leg, only a mild itch when the fish try to eat the blood that pours from the two tiny spots where the snake's teeth penetrated my skin.

I also have about 100 million different instruments that I mess around with, much to the delight/annoyance of whoever may be my roommate. My fraternity occupies a good deal of my time since a lot of my best friends are also in Sigma Nu. We're a pretty laid back group of guys, and we definitely don't live up to the 'frat' stereotype.
